metadata.name: Memo #229
metadata.description:
Memo is a abstract expression of memories written on small pieces of paper, pictures of important moments or a reminder of all the things You have forgotten.

Memo is created with P5JS. Large number of rectangles are packed in loops to the canvas with a random rectangle packing algorithm with simple collision detection. 
The looped area varies from 1 vertical or horizontal rectangle to 8x8 grid. Packed area is created with simple random walking grid loop.
60+ color palettes are handpicked and they can appear reversed. 
One random palette is picked for each piece and p5js.noise() drives the colors, size and angle on the rects with lots of attributes.

Click 'n' to add white noise.
Click 's' to save image as jpeg.

Click '1' to 1x pixelDensity(3600 x 6400 or 6400 x 3600 px - default).
Click '2' to 2x pixelDensity(7200 x 12800 or 12800 x 7200 px).

VGA 2022 / CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Ambiguous Instances #109
metadata.description:
“Ambiguous Instances” is the sixth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

Often people use a specific example to argue their point of view. Unfortunately, this means that they can completely make it up or hyperbolise it to benefit their views, which means that it's a completely invalid argument.

Statistics, on the other hand, cannot lie, since they are just pure observations.
That is unless they are completely made up, of course.

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #66
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #436
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd

metadata.name: THE400FLIPS #315
metadata.description:
The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain


Controls:

[s] save as PNG.
[a] render alternate higher resolution artwork (takes a few seconds).
[z] save alternate artwork as PNG.


Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #22
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid
